content.description:
A fine offwidth established by Bob Boyles in the mid 70s.

About the route, Bob offers the following observations:

“The distance between the good pro is rather far and I'm sure I would have grounded out if I popped out higher up. I always thought the "wounded" knee jam lower down was the crux. That's where you have to pull your knee out where the crack pinches down a bit.”
content.protection:
Route can be protected by bumping up a #7 camalot. There's at least one place for a #6 camalot partway up the pillar. Reportedly a #4 (blue) big bro can also be useful, if you're into that kind of thing.

Chain anchors recently equipped with the go-ahead from first ascensionist.
content.location:
You can’t miss this obvious, gaping offwidth staring you in the face as you walk to the back of the canyon.

Just a few feet right of the bolts for Pabst Smear.

content.description: No distinct crux, maybe tougher the higher you go. Fun traverse to anchors of Circuit Breaker.
content.protection: Very thin. TR. Anchors of Circuit Breaker
content.location: Dihedral just left of Circuit Breaker.

content.description: Follow the finger crack in the corner. Don't miss all the good holds on the arête to the left. If you finish straight up the finishing move to the anchor is really hard! You can also finish up and right and then traverse back left if you can't get the last move.
content.protection: Lots of small cams and nuts. Two bolt anchor. The pro is small but you can sew it up.
content.location: Just to the right of Pabst Smear. Starts on top of an 8 foot ledge.

content.description: Fun dihedral stemming leads to an overhanging finish on positive holds. Great climb!
content.protection: 6 bolts to chains
content.location: About 20 feet left of Pabst Smear.

content.description: Fun climbing that starts out easy in a small vertical open book with a crack and ample holds.  At the top of the open book move right and get ready for the business!  Ascend the overhanging corner/finger-crack above to the anchors.
content.protection:
6 bolts + a 2 bolt anchor.

This is another route that originally went on gear and was subsequently retro-bolted.  Lots of opportunity for good gear in the initial open book, with some potential for more creative placements up higher...
content.location: Open book a few feet right of the flying circus.

content.description: Straightforward 5” offwidth crack with plenty of constrictions offering very secure feet.
content.protection: Gear to 5”. Use the anchors for the Standard to descend.
content.location: Start is the same as the Standard, but instead of climbing the chimney behind the column, ascend the offwidth crack to the left (you’re climbing the same column as Wounded Knee but from the other side.)

content.description: A very fun addition to West Carbody. Stick-clip the first bolt or clip it from the Velcro Fly start column. The first 4 bolts are characterized by good quality Black Cliffs 5.10+ arete climbing on interesting holds. Cop a rest when you can on the blocky section near the top , clip that last bolt, and punch it through an overhanging boulder problem to the anchors. It is possible to clip the last bolt and skirt out right to the Velcro Fly anchors to avoid the 5.11d+ crux
content.protection: 5 bolts to quick clip anchors. Be careful at the second bolt, a blown clip would likely be a ground fall.
content.location: Just right of Pabst Smear.

content.description: One of the original black cliffs climbs. Route starts in a chimney right above a fallen column. Ample holds, easy chimney, and takes good pro.
content.protection: Takes good pro. New anchors with rap rings near the top. If you want to do it as the original route, climb to the top and over the lip. West car body descent is just downstream from the car body canyon.
content.location: This route is immediately above an obvious fallen column.

content.description: Technical and sustained climbing using various small holds the whole way.  The reach from the final stance to the anchors is long and could prove problematic for the vertically challenged . . .
content.protection: 6 bolts to 2 bolt anchor and chains.  The moves to reach the first bolt are tough . . .
content.location: Between the Throb and the Flying Circus

content.description:
Technical and sustained palming, smearing, and stemming.  Don't underestimate the finish, this route doesn't let up until you are at the anchor!

Apparently this route originally went on gear and was subsequently retro-bolted.  Without the bolts the pro looked like it would be very thin and tricky! What a bold FA!
content.protection: 6 bolts to 2 rap hangers
content.location: The bolted line between the two obvious offwidths.

content.description: This is a very entertaining climb!  It follows a finger crack up a corner, with plenty of edges for your feet for *most* of the climb.  The crux is in the middle and involves a few moves without the straightforward feet, but with good finger locks.  The moves at the top are fun too, and easier than they look from below.
content.protection: Pro to 1", with and emphasis on finger sized pieces.  2 bolt anchor
content.location: The crack/dihedral just right of the bolted line, Lizard Breath.

content.description: A delicate and engaging thin seam just to the right of The Throb. I think the intended line goes directly up and right to the anchors on Kaopectate, but you can also finish left on The Throb with good pro and exciting movement. One of the best cracks at the cliffs!
content.protection: Small gear and large cojones. lots of micro cams 0.3 and smaller and tiny nuts, 2-3 bolts protect the left finish. Ball nuts or 000 C3's might be useful. A bold lead, most will probably prefer a toprope from the anchors for The Throb.
content.location: About 5ft to the right of The Throb.

content.description: Fun climb with slightly slopey holds near the bottom that become more positive as you get higher up.
content.protection: 6 bolts to chains
content.location: Just to the left of Ohm's Law.

content.description: Crack to Flying Circus anchors.  Starts low with hand jams and quickly turns to standard Black Cliffs "sport climbing while plugging gear in a crack".  One loose block at the top that's marked, but doesn't appear to be going anywhere.  After I climbed it, I rapped the route and cleaned off all the loose stuff I could find so it's good to go.
content.protection: Standard rack to chains
content.location: Just left of Flying Circus and Pictures of Lily.  Shares chains with Flying Circus.  See pic.

content.description: Crack directly right of Row Your Boat. Follow the crack to the top of the pillar, then head left to the Row Your Boat anchors. Alternatively, head right for a 5.10d variation, but with no anchors.
content.protection: .75 to #2 BD, and either clip the last bolt of Row your boat or take a small piece for the last section.
content.location: crack to the right of Row your Boat

content.description: Is the climb fried or are you?  Small edges interspersed with rest jugs climb the middle of the pillar followed by a brief roof to reach the chains.
content.protection: 5-6 draws plus 2 anchor draws.
content.location: Start on Bolts-N-Burger.  Clip the first bolt then traverse left onto the next column.  Follow the bolt line up to the chains.

content.description: Superb jamming up a hand crack with a crux move to the anchors on top.  Excellent!
content.protection: Single rack to 2" should have you nicely protected. 2 bolt anchor with chains.
content.location: Towards the right end of the wall about 30 feet past the Doug Scott Route.

content.description: Yet another retro-bolted crack climb.  This climb follows a nice finger crack for most of it's length, and then moves right at the top to join the anchors for Thursday Knights.  Fun moves and good pro!
content.protection: 5 bolts (all within a foot or two of an excellent crack) to 2 bolt anchor, OR a selection of finger sized pieces.  There are many excellent nut placements.
content.location: The obvious crack just left of Thursday Knights.

content.description:
Fun jammin!  Sandy Epeldi's book describes this as "the best jam crack in the area."  The crack starts about 15 off the deck and there isn't much for pro before that.

Watch for nested owls after the roof at the end of the crack.
content.protection: standard rack to rap hangers.  You may be able to protect the final moves to reach the crack with a micro-nut.
content.location: The obvious straight-in jam crack about 2/3 the way from the left end of the wall.

content.description: Climb up bolted column face without straying into Bolts and Burgers on the left or the sweet looking hand crack on the right.  Crimpy crux near the top of the pillar.  Mantle onto the top of the pillar, clip the last bolt, and then a few more easy moves land you at the chains.
content.protection: 4 bolts to chains
content.location: Just right of Bolts and Burgers and left of a pretty hand crack

climbs.name: Dos Pescadores
climbs.fa: Steve Fransen, T. Hamilton, & B. Whitney

content.description: Start on Thursday Knights, but cut right after the 3rd bolt. Get a good rest on the ledge before the finish, then climb up an overhanging face with impeccable rock using widely spaced finger locks. Tough finishing moves!
content.protection: 7 bolts to chains
content.location: Just right of Thursday Knights

content.description: Typical sport route for this area. Crux between 2nd & 3rd bolts; take care not to blow the 3rd clip as it could hurt.
content.protection: 5 bolts to chains
content.location: squeezed between Barry, Barry & Constant Current

content.description: Weird thought-provoking moves.  It's all there but not exactly obvious (at least to me).  Greasy on a hot day.  This climb is a bit spicy due to interesting bolt placement that puts you in ledge-fall territory near the second AND third bolts.
content.protection: 5 bolts to a 2-bolt anchor.  Bolt one is low (basically pointless except to keep you from bouncing off the ledge), and there is a bit of a runout to bolt 3.  You may want to supplement the bolts with a set of nuts or small cams since it looked like this climb would protect well with gear.  Apparently the route was originally done without the bolts...
content.location: Just left of the excellent climb Barry, Barry.

content.description: Another great Black Cliffs trad climb that demands a variety of crack climbing skills! Start in a corner with sweet double cracks that go from wide hands to fists. After topping out on the column on the left side, get ready for some perfect finger locks. Entertaining face climbing follows all the way to the anchors. Great climb, and a bit of a proud lead for a 5.8. Edit: Two photos show two different routes. The darker photo is Constant Current, the lighter photo is actually Barry Barry.
content.protection: Single rack to 3 inches, with an emphasis on finger sized gear for the second half of the route.
content.location: The obvious double cracks 20ft right of Barry, Barry.

content.description: Extremely fun climbing up a pronounced column.  Weave between the left, right, and center of the column as you go.  As usual for the Black Cliffs, the finishing moves do not disappoint!
content.protection: 6 bolts to chains
content.location: The next bolted route to the right of Crunchy Frogs up the obvious column.

content.description: The crux is at the top.
content.protection: 6 bolts to chains
content.location: Right of French Fried and left of Row Your Boat

content.description: Fun face climbing with good protection where you need it.  Nice steep finish.
content.protection: Standard rack to #1 C4. Bolted anchor.
content.location: Near the left end of the wall, just to the right of Crunchy Frogs.
